	<subsection label="separability-of-a-DE">
		<title>Separable Differential Equations</title>
	
		<p>
			Separable equations are often not presented in a <xref ref="separable" text="custom">separable form</xref>. In such cases, you'll need to rewrite the equation to verify it's separable. This process typically involves two main steps:
			<ol>
				<li>
					<p>
						<term>Isolate the derivative</term> on one side of the equation <m>\left(\dfrac{dy}{dx} = \ldots\right)</m>,
					</p>
				</li>
				<li>
					<p>
						Then form the product on the other side <m>\left(\dfrac{dy}{dx} = f(x) \cdot g(y)\right)</m>.
					</p>
				</li>
			</ol>
		</p>

		<p>
			Common algebra techniques to achieve this product include:
			<dl width="wide">
				<li xml:id="sums-to-products">
					<title>Sums ‚ûú Products</title>
					<m>\quad ab + ac = a \cdot (b + c)</m>
				</li>
				<li xml:id="exponents-to-products">
					<title>Exponents ‚ûú Products</title>
					<m>\quad a^{m + n} = a^m \cdot a^{n}</m>, <m>\quad a^{m - n} = \sfrac{a^m}{a^n}</m>
				</li>
				<li xml:id="fractions-to-products">
					<title>Fractions ‚ûú Products</title> 
					<m>\quad \dfrac{a}{b} = \dfrac{a}{1} \cdot \dfrac{1}{b}</m>,
					<m>\quad \dfrac{ab}{cd} = \dfrac{a}{c} \cdot \dfrac{b}{d}</m>
				</li>
			</dl>
		</p>

		<p>
			To illustrate this, consider the following warm-up examples.
		</p>

		<paragraphs>
			<title>Warm-Up Examples</title>
			<p>
				Show that the differential equations are separable.
			</p>

			<example xml:id="example-show-separable-warmup-1">
				<statement><p><m>y' = yt^2 - y</m></p></statement>

				<solution>
					<p>
						To show this equation is seperable, we convert <xref ref="sums-to-products" text="title"/> by factoring out the common <m>y</m>:
						<me>
							y' = \ub{y \cdot (t^2 - 1)}_{f(t)\ \cdot\ g(y)} \quad\leftarrow\text{separable}.
						</me>
					</p>
				</solution>
			</example>

			<example xml:id="example-show-separable-warmup-2">
				<statement><p><m>y' + 18xy = 6x</m></p></statement>

				<solution>
					<p>
						This time we isolate <m>y'</m> first, then factor out <m>x</m>:
						<me>
							y' = 6x - 18xy = 6x \cdot \left(1 - 3y\right) \quad\leftarrow\textit{separable}.
						</me>
					</p>
				</solution>
			</example>

			<example xml:id="example-show-separable-warmup-3">
				<statement><p><m>yy' - 1 = x</m></p></statement>

				<solution>
					<p>
						First, isolate <m>y'</m>:
						<me>
							yy' = x + 1 \quad \Rightarrow \quad y' = \frac{x + 1}{y},
						</me>
						then split the single fraction as a product of fractions:
						<me>
							y' 
								= \frac{x + 1}{1} \cdot \frac{1}{y} 
								= \ub{(x+1) \cdot \frac{1}{y}}_{f(x)\ \cdot\ g(y)} \quad \leftarrow \text{separable}.
						</me>
					</p>
				</solution>
			</example>

			<example xml:id="example-show-separable-warmup-4">
				<statement><p><m>y' = e^{x+y}</m></p></statement>

				<solution>
					<p>
						At first glance, this doesn't look separable because of the <m>x+y</m>, but applying <xref ref="exponents-to-products" text="title"/> we get: 
						<me>
							y' = e^{x+y} = \ub{e^x \cdot e^{y}}_{f(x)\ \cdot\ g(y)} \quad\leftarrow\text{separable}.
						</me>
					</p>
				</solution>
			</example>
		</paragraphs>

		<p>
			The next set of examples require a bit more work to show that they are separable.
		</p>

		<paragraphs>
			<title>Challenging Examples</title>

			<p>
				Show that the differential equations are separable.
			</p>

			<example xml:id="example-show-separable-1">
				<statement><p><m>P^2\dfrac{dP}{dt} + \dfrac{dP}{dt} = Pt</m></p></statement>

				<solution>
					<p>
						Since the variables in this equation are <m>t</m> and <m>P</m>, the separable form will look like
						<me>\dfrac{dP}{dt} = f(P) \cdot g(t)</me>.
					</p>

					<p>
						To get there, we isolate <m>dP/dt</m> first:
						<md>
							<mrow> P^2\dfrac{dP}{dt} + \dfrac{dP}{dt} \amp = Pt </mrow>
							<mrow> (1+P^2)\dfrac{dP}{dt} \amp = Pt </mrow>
							<mrow> \dfrac{dP}{dt} \amp = \dfrac{Pt}{1+P^2}. </mrow>
						</md>
					</p>

					<p>
						Now, we split the fraction so that <m>P</m> and <m>t</m> can be separated:
						<me>
							\dfrac{dP}{dt}
								= \dfrac{P\cdot t}{(P^2 + 1) \cdot (1)}
								= \ub{
									{\color{RoyalBlue}	\os{f(P)}{\os{\downarrow}{	\dfrac{P}{P^2 + 1}}}		} \cdot
									{\color{green}	\os{g(t)}{\os{\downarrow}{	\dfrac{t}{1}}}			}
								}_{\text{separable form}}.
						</me>
						So, the equation is <em>separable</em>.
					</p>
				</solution>
			</example>

			<!-- <example xml:id="example-show-separable-2">
				<statement><p><m>\dfrac{dM}{d\omega} - 11e^{\omega + 3M} = 0</m></p></statement>

				<solution>
					<p>
						Isolating the derivative and applying <m>e^{A + B} = e^{A} \cdot e^{B}</m> leads to the separable form:
						<me>
							\dfrac{dM}{d\omega}
								= 11e^{\omega + 3M}
								= 11(e^{\omega} \cdot e^{3M})
								= \ub{
									{\color{RoyalBlue} \os{f(\omega)}{ \os{\downarrow}{ 11e^{\omega} }}	} \cdot
									{\color{green}\os{g(M)}{ \os{\downarrow}{ e^{3M} }}	}
								}_{\text{separable form}}.
						</me>
					</p>
				</solution>
			</example> -->

			<example xml:id="example-show-separable-3">
				<statement><p><m>y\dfrac{dy}{dx} + 8x^2e^{x + \cos y} = 6x^2e^x</m></p></statement>

				<solution>
					<p>
						This example uses a little of everything we discussed, so strap in.
					</p>

					<p>
						Noticing that the equation is first-order, we start by isolating <m>dy/dx</m>
						<md>
							<mrow>
								y\dfrac{dy}{dx} + 8x^2e^{x + \cos y} = 6x^2e^x
							</mrow>
							<mrow>
								\dfrac{dy}{dx} = \dfrac{6x^2e^x - 8x^2e^{x + \cos y}}{y}
							</mrow>
						</md>
					</p>

					<p>
						Next, we can rewrite the exponent in the numerator as a product
						<me>
							\dfrac{dy}{dx} = \dfrac{6x^2e^x - 8x^2e^{x}e^{\cos y}}{y}
						</me>
						and recognize that there is a common factor in the numerator
						<me>
							\dfrac{dy}{dx} = \dfrac{2x^2e^x(3 - 4e^{\cos y})}{y}
						</me>.
					</p>

					<p>
						From here, we write the result as a product of fractions,
						<me>
							\dfrac{dy}{dx} = \dfrac{2x^2e^x}{1} \cdot \dfrac{3 - 4e^{\cos y}}{y}
						</me>,
						and the equation is now clearly <em>separable</em>.
					</p>
				</solution>
			</example>
		</paragraphs>

		<p>
			As important as it is to show an equation is separable, it is equally important to identify when it is not.
		</p>

		<example xml:id="example-show-separable-4">
			<statement>
				<p>
					Show the differential equations are NOT separable.
					<me>
						y^2\dfrac{d^2y}{dx^2} = x, \qquad
						xy' + 3x = y.
					</me>
				</p>
			</statement>

			<solution>
				<p>
					The first equation is a bit of a trick question to remind you of the first-order requirement of a separable equation. Since this equation is second-order, <em>separability does not apply</em>.
				</p>

				<p>
					This equation is first-order, but it is not separable. To see this, we can rearrange the equation to isolate the derivative:
					<md>
						<mrow> xy' + 3x = y </mrow>
						<mrow> xy' = y - 3x </mrow>
						<mrow> y' = \dfrac{y - 3x}{x} </mrow>
					</md>.
					Since there is no common factor of <m>x</m> or <m>y</m> in the numerator, the variables cannot be separated and the equation is not separable.
				</p>
			</solution>
		</example>

		<p>
			Learning to recognize when an equation is separable is the first and most important step in applying the method of separation of variables. In the next section, we'll see how this recognition leads to actual solutions.
		</p>

