						<row><cell><m/></cell></row>
					</tabular>
				</areas>
				<feedback>
					<p>
						A differential equation is separable if you can rearrange it to express it as a product of functions involving only <m>x</m> and <m>y</m> separately. Look for equations that can be manipulated into this form, even if they do not initially appear separable.
					</p>
				</feedback>
			</task>
		</exercise>
	</subsection>

	<outcomes label="separable-eqns-takeaways">
		<ul marker="square">
			<li>
				<p>
					<m>\textit{Separable}</m> means the differential equation is first-order and right-hand side factors as a product of an <m>x</m>-only part and a <m>y</m>-only part:
					<me>\dfrac{dy}{dx}=f(x)\cdot g(y)</me>.
				</p>
			</li>
			<li>
				<p>
					We care about a differential equation being separable because it is a requirement for the seperation of variables method (next section).  
				</p>
			</li>
			<li>
				<p>
					Use algebra to reveal the product: factor common terms, split exponentials <m>e^{A+B}=e^A e^B</m>, and rearrange fractions <m>\dfrac{A\cdot B}{C\cdot D}=\dfrac{A}{C}\cdot\dfrac{B}{D}</m>.
				</p>
			</li>
		</ul>
	</outcomes>

</section>